{"nodes":[{"content":"BitLocker Group Policy settings (Windows 10)","pos":[11,55]},{"content":"This topic for IT professionals describes the function, location, and effect of each Group Policy setting that is used to manage BitLocker Drive Encryption.","pos":[69,225]},{"content":"BitLocker Group Policy settings","pos":[381,412]},{"content":"Applies to","pos":[416,426]},{"content":"Windows 10","pos":[433,443]},{"content":"This topic for IT professionals describes the function, location, and effect of each Group Policy setting that is used to manage BitLocker Drive Encryption.","pos":[445,601]},{"content":"To control what drive encryption tasks the user can perform from the Windows Control Panel or to modify other configuration options, you can use Group Policy administrative templates or local computer policy settings.","pos":[603,820]},{"content":"How you configure these policy settings depends on how you implement BitLocker and what level of user interaction will be allowed.","pos":[821,951]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Note:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>  A separate set of Group Policy settings supports the use of the Trusted Platform Module (TPM).","pos":[954,1059]},{"content":"For details about those settings, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Trusted Platform Module Group Policy settings<ept id=\"p1\">](trusted-platform-module-services-group-policy-settings.md)</ept>.","pos":[1060,1205]},{"content":"BitLocker Group Policy settings can be accessed using the Local Group Policy Editor and the Group Policy Management Console (GPMC) under <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Computer Configuration<ph id=\"ph1\">\\\\</ph>Administrative Templates<ph id=\"ph2\">\\\\</ph>Windows Components<ph id=\"ph3\">\\\\</ph>BitLocker Drive Encryption<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.","pos":[1208,1446]},{"content":"Most of the BitLocker Group Policy settings are applied when BitLocker is initially turned on for a drive.","pos":[1447,1553]},{"content":"If a computer is not compliant with existing Group Policy settings, BitLocker may not be turned on or modified until the computer is in a compliant state.","pos":[1554,1708]},{"content":"When a drive is out of compliance with Group Policy settings (for example, if a Group Policy setting was changed after the initial BitLocker deployment in your organization, and then the setting was applied to previously encrypted drives), no change can be made to the BitLocker configuration of that drive except a change that will bring it into compliance.","pos":[1709,2067]},{"content":"If multiple changes are necessary to bring the drive into compliance, you must suspend BitLocker protection, make the necessary changes, and then resume protection.","pos":[2069,2233]},{"content":"This situation could occur, for example, if a removable drive was initially configured to be unlocked with a password and then Group Policy settings are changed to disallow passwords and require smart cards.","pos":[2234,2442]},{"content":"In this situation, you need to suspend BitLocker protection by using the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Manage-bde<ept id=\"p1\">](http://technet.microsoft.com/library/ff829849.aspx)</ept> command-line tool, delete the password unlock method, and add the smart card method.","pos":[2443,2665]},{"content":"After this is complete, BitLocker is compliant with the Group Policy setting and BitLocker protection on the drive can be resumed.","pos":[2666,2796]},{"pos":[2832,2863],"content":"BitLocker Group Policy settings"},{"content":"The following sections provide a comprehensive list of BitLocker Group Policy settings that are organized by usage.","pos":[2865,2980]},{"content":"BitLocker Group Policy settings include settings for specific drive types (operating system drives, fixed data drives, and removable data drives) and settings that are applied to all drives.","pos":[2981,3171]},{"content":"The following policy settings can be used to determine how a BitLocker-protected drive can be unlocked.","pos":[3173,3276]},{"content":"Allow network unlock at startup","pos":[3283,3314]},{"content":"Require additional authentication at startup","pos":[3338,3382]},{"content":"Allow enhanced PINs for startup","pos":[3407,3438]},{"content":"Configure minimum PIN length for startup","pos":[3463,3503]},{"content":"Disallow standard users from changing the PIN or password","pos":[3528,3585]},{"content":"Configure use of passwords for operating system drives","pos":[3610,3664]},{"content":"Require additional authentication at startup (Windows Server 2008 and Windows Vista)","pos":[3683,3767]},{"content":"Configure use of smart cards on fixed data drives","pos":[3792,3841]},{"content":"Configure use of passwords on fixed data drives","pos":[3866,3913]},{"content":"Configure use of smart cards on removable data drives","pos":[3938,3991]},{"content":"Configure use of passwords on removable data drives","pos":[4016,4067]},{"content":"Validate smart card certificate usage rule compliance","pos":[4092,4145]},{"content":"Enable use of BitLocker authentication requiring preboot keyboard input on slates","pos":[4170,4251]},{"content":"The following policy settings are used to control how users can access drives and how they can use BitLocker on their computers.","pos":[4268,4396]},{"content":"Deny write access to fixed drives not protected by BitLocker","pos":[4403,4463]},{"content":"Deny write access to removable drives not protected by BitLocker","pos":[4490,4554]},{"content":"Control use of BitLocker on removable drives","pos":[4581,4625]},{"content":"The following policy settings determine the encryption methods and encryption types that are used with BitLocker.","pos":[4648,4761]},{"content":"Choose drive encryption method and cipher strength","pos":[4768,4818]},{"content":"Configure use of hardware-based encryption for fixed data drives","pos":[4844,4908]},{"content":"Configure use of hardware-based encryption for operating system drives","pos":[4929,4999]},{"content":"Configure use of hardware-based encryption for removable data drives","pos":[5020,5088]},{"content":"Enforce drive encryption type on fixed data drives","pos":[5109,5159]},{"content":"Enforce drive encryption type on operating system drives","pos":[5183,5239]},{"content":"Enforce drive encryption type on removable data drives","pos":[5263,5317]},{"content":"The following policy settings define the recovery methods that can be used to restore access to a BitLocker-protected drive if an authentication method fails or is unable to be used.","pos":[5337,5519]},{"content":"Choose how BitLocker-protected operating system drives can be recovered","pos":[5526,5597]},{"content":"Choose how users can recover BitLocker-protected drives (Windows Server 2008 and Windows Vista)","pos":[5616,5711]},{"content":"Store BitLocker recovery information in Active Directory Domain Services (Windows Server 2008 and Windows Vista)","pos":[5730,5842]},{"content":"Choose default folder for recovery password","pos":[5861,5904]},{"content":"Choose how BitLocker-protected fixed drives can be recovered","pos":[5923,5983]},{"content":"Choose how BitLocker-protected removable drives can be recovered","pos":[6002,6066]},{"content":"Configure the pre-boot recovery message and URL","pos":[6085,6132]},{"content":"The following policies are used to support customized deployment scenarios in your organization.","pos":[6159,6255]},{"content":"Allow Secure Boot for integrity validation","pos":[6262,6304]},{"content":"Provide the unique identifiers for your organization","pos":[6326,6378]},{"content":"Prevent memory overwrite on restart","pos":[6400,6435]},{"content":"Configure TPM platform validation profile for BIOS-based firmware configurations","pos":[6457,6537]},{"content":"Configure TPM platform validation profile (Windows Vista, Windows Server 2008, Windows 7, Windows Server 2008 R2)","pos":[6559,6672]},{"content":"Configure TPM platform validation profile for native UEFI firmware configurations","pos":[6694,6775]},{"content":"Reset platform validation data after BitLocker recovery","pos":[6800,6855]},{"content":"Use enhanced Boot Configuration Data validation profile","pos":[6878,6933]},{"content":"Allow access to BitLocker-protected fixed data drives from earlier versions of Windows","pos":[6953,7039]},{"content":"Allow access to BitLocker-protected removable data drives from earlier versions of Windows","pos":[7061,7151]},{"pos":[7208,7239],"content":"Allow network unlock at startup"},{"content":"This policy controls a portion of the behavior of the Network Unlock feature in BitLocker.","pos":[7241,7331]},{"content":"This policy is required to enable BitLocker Network Unlock on a network because it allows clients running BitLocker to create the necessary network key protector during encryption.","pos":[7332,7512]},{"content":"This policy is used in addition to the BitLocker Drive Encryption Network Unlock Certificate security policy (located in the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Public Key Policies<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> folder of Local Computer Policy) to allow systems that are connected to a trusted network to properly utilize the Network Unlock feature.","pos":[7513,7799]},{"content":"Policy description","pos":[7926,7944]},{"content":"With this policy setting, you can control whether a BitLocker-protected computer that is connected to a trusted local area network and joined to a domain can create and use network key protectors on TPM-enabled computers to automatically unlock the operating system drive when the computer is started.","pos":[7983,8284]},{"content":"Introduced","pos":[8346,8356]},{"content":"Windows Server 2012 and Windows 8","pos":[8395,8428]},{"content":"Drive type","pos":[8489,8499]},{"content":"Operating system drives","pos":[8538,8561]},{"content":"Policy path","pos":[8623,8634]},{"content":"Computer Configuration\\Administrative Templates\\Windows Components\\BitLocker Drive Encryption\\Operating System Drives","pos":[8673,8790]},{"content":"Conflicts","pos":[8851,8860]},{"content":"None","pos":[8899,8903]},{"content":"When enabled","pos":[8965,8977]},{"content":"Clients configured with a BitLocker Network Unlock certificate can create and use Network Key Protectors.","pos":[9016,9121]},{"content":"When disabled or not configured","pos":[9182,9213]},{"content":"Clients cannot create and use Network Key Protectors","pos":[9252,9304]},{"content":"Reference","pos":[9342,9351]},{"content":"To use a network key protector to unlock the computer, the computer and the server that hosts BitLocker Drive Encryption Network Unlock must be provisioned with a Network Unlock certificate.","pos":[9355,9545]},{"content":"The Network Unlock certificate is used to create a network key protector and to protect the information exchange with the server to unlock the computer.","pos":[9546,9698]},{"content":"You can use the Group Policy setting <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Computer Configuration<ph id=\"ph1\">\\\\</ph>Windows Settings<ph id=\"ph2\">\\\\</ph>Security Settings<ph id=\"ph3\">\\\\</ph>Public Key Policies<ph id=\"ph4\">\\\\</ph>BitLocker Drive Encryption Network Unlock Certificate<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> on the domain controller to distribute this certificate to computers in your organization.","pos":[9699,9966]},{"content":"This unlock method uses the TPM on the computer, so computers that do not have a TPM cannot create network key protectors to automatically unlock by using Network Unlock.","pos":[9967,10137]},{"pos":[10140,10354],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Note:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>  For reliability and security, computers should also have a TPM startup PIN that can be used when the computer is disconnected from the wired network or cannot connect to the domain controller at startup."},{"pos":[10357,10489],"content":"For more information about Network Unlock, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>BitLocker: How to enable Network Unlock<ept id=\"p1\">](bitlocker-how-to-enable-network-unlock.md)</ept>."},{"pos":[10531,10575],"content":"Require additional authentication at startup"},{"content":"This policy setting is used to control which unlock options are available for operating system drives.","pos":[10577,10679]},{"content":"Policy description","pos":[10805,10823]},{"content":"With this policy setting, you can configure whether BitLocker requires additional authentication each time the computer starts and whether you are using BitLocker with a Trusted Platform Module (TPM).","pos":[10862,11062]},{"content":"This policy setting is applied when you turn on BitLocker.","pos":[11063,11121]},{"content":"Introduced","pos":[11183,11193]},{"content":"Windows Server 2008 R2 and Windows 7","pos":[11232,11268]},{"content":"Drive type","pos":[11329,11339]},{"content":"Operating system drives","pos":[11378,11401]},{"content":"Policy path","pos":[11463,11474]},{"content":"Computer Configuration\\Administrative Templates\\Windows Components\\BitLocker Drive Encryption\\Operating System Drives","pos":[11513,11630]},{"content":"Conflicts","pos":[11691,11700]},{"content":"If one authentication method is required, the other methods cannot be allowed.","pos":[11739,11817]},{"content":"Use of BitLocker with a TPM startup key or with a TPM startup key and a PIN must be disallowed if the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;strong&gt;</ph>Deny write access to removable drives not protected by BitLocker<ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/strong&gt;</ph> policy setting is enabled.","pos":[11825,12035]},{"content":"When enabled","pos":[12097,12109]},{"content":"Users can configure advanced startup options in the BitLocker Setup Wizard.","pos":[12148,12223]},{"content":"When disabled or not configured","pos":[12284,12315]},{"content":"Users can configure only basic options on computers with a TPM.","pos":[12354,12417]},{"content":"Only one of the additional authentication options can be required at startup; otherwise, a policy error occurs.","pos":[12425,12536]},{"content":"Reference","pos":[12574,12583]},{"content":"If you want to use BitLocker on a computer without a TPM, select the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Allow BitLocker without a compatible TPM<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> check box.","pos":[12587,12711]},{"content":"In this mode, a USB drive is required for startup.","pos":[12712,12762]},{"content":"Key information that is used to encrypt the drive is stored on the USB drive, which creates a USB key.","pos":[12763,12865]},{"content":"When the USB key is inserted, access to the drive is authenticated and the drive is accessible.","pos":[12866,12961]},{"content":"If the USB key is lost or unavailable, you need to use one of the BitLocker recovery options to access the drive.","pos":[12962,13075]},{"content":"On a computer with a compatible TPM, four types of authentication methods can be used at startup to provide added protection for encrypted data.","pos":[13077,13221]},{"content":"When the computer starts, it can use:","pos":[13222,13259]},{"content":"only the TPM for authentication","pos":[13265,13296]},{"content":"insertion of a USB flash drive containing the startup key","pos":[13301,13358]},{"content":"the entry of a 4-digit to 20-digit personal identification number (PIN)","pos":[13363,13434]},{"content":"a combination of the PIN and the USB flash drive","pos":[13439,13487]},{"content":"There are four options for TPM-enabled computers or devices:","pos":[13489,13549]},{"content":"Configure TPM startup","pos":[13555,13576]},{"content":"Allow TPM","pos":[13586,13595]},{"content":"Require TPM","pos":[13604,13615]},{"content":"Do not allow TPM","pos":[13624,13640]},{"content":"Configure TPM startup PIN","pos":[13645,13670]},{"content":"Allow startup PIN with TPM","pos":[13680,13706]},{"content":"Require startup PIN with TPM","pos":[13715,13743]},{"content":"Do not allow startup PIN with TPM","pos":[13752,13785]},{"content":"Configure TPM startup key","pos":[13790,13815]},{"content":"Allow startup key with TPM","pos":[13825,13851]},{"content":"Require startup key with TPM","pos":[13860,13888]},{"content":"Do not allow startup key with TPM","pos":[13897,13930]},{"content":"Configure TPM startup key and PIN","pos":[13935,13968]},{"content":"Allow TPM startup key with PIN","pos":[13978,14008]},{"content":"Require startup key and PIN with TPM","pos":[14017,14053]},{"content":"Do not allow TPM startup key with PIN","pos":[14062,14099]},{"pos":[14141,14172],"content":"Allow enhanced PINs for startup"},{"content":"This policy setting permits the use of enhanced PINs when you use an unlock method that includes a PIN.","pos":[14174,14277]},{"content":"Policy description","pos":[14403,14421]},{"content":"With this policy setting, you can configure whether enhanced startup PINs are used with BitLocker.","pos":[14460,14558]},{"content":"Introduced","pos":[14620,14630]},{"content":"Windows Server 2008 R2 and Windows 7","pos":[14669,14705]},{"content":"Drive type","pos":[14766,14776]},{"content":"Operating system drives","pos":[14815,14838]},{"content":"Policy path","pos":[14900,14911]},{"content":"Computer Configuration\\Administrative Templates\\Windows Components\\BitLocker Drive Encryption\\Operating System Drives","pos":[14950,15067]},{"content":"Conflicts","pos":[15128,15137]},{"content":"None","pos":[15176,15180]},{"content":"When enabled","pos":[15242,15254]},{"content":"All new BitLocker startup PINs that are set will be enhanced PINs.","pos":[15293,15359]},{"content":"Existing drives that were protected by using standard startup PINs are not affected.","pos":[15360,15444]},{"content":"When disabled or not configured","pos":[15505,15536]},{"content":"Enhanced PINs will not be used.","pos":[15575,15606]},{"content":"Reference","pos":[15645,15654]},{"content":"Enhanced startup PINs permit the use of characters (including uppercase and lowercase letters, symbols, numbers, and spaces).","pos":[15658,15783]},{"content":"This policy setting is applied when you turn on BitLocker.","pos":[15784,15842]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Important:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>  Not all computers support enhanced PIN characters in the preboot environment.","pos":[15845,15938]},{"content":"It is strongly recommended that users perform a system check during the BitLocker setup to verify that enhanced PIN characters can be used.","pos":[15939,16078]},{"pos":[16121,16161],"content":"Configure minimum PIN length for startup"},{"content":"This policy setting is used to set a minimum PIN length when you use an unlock method that includes a PIN.","pos":[16163,16269]},{"content":"Policy description","pos":[16395,16413]},{"content":"With this policy setting, you can configure a minimum length for a TPM startup PIN.","pos":[16452,16535]},{"content":"This policy setting is applied when you turn on BitLocker.","pos":[16536,16594]},{"content":"The startup PIN must have a minimum length of 4 digits, and it can have a maximum length of 20 digits.","pos":[16595,16697]},{"content":"Introduced","pos":[16759,16769]},{"content":"Windows Server 2008 R2 and Windows 7","pos":[16808,16844]},{"content":"Drive type","pos":[16905,16915]},{"content":"Operating system drives","pos":[16954,16977]},{"content":"Policy path","pos":[17039,17050]},{"content":"Computer Configuration\\Administrative Templates\\Windows Components\\BitLocker Drive Encryption\\Operating System Drives","pos":[17089,17206]},{"content":"Conflicts","pos":[17267,17276]},{"content":"None","pos":[17315,17319]},{"content":"When enabled","pos":[17381,17393]},{"content":"You can require that users enter a minimum number of digits to when setting their startup PINs.","pos":[17432,17527]},{"content":"When disabled or not configured","pos":[17588,17619]},{"content":"Users can configure a startup PIN of any length between 4 and 20 digits.","pos":[17658,17730]},{"content":"Reference","pos":[17768,17777]},{"content":"This policy setting is applied when you turn on BitLocker.","pos":[17781,17839]},{"content":"The startup PIN must have a minimum length of 4 digits and can have a maximum length of 20 digits.","pos":[17840,17938]},{"pos":[17980,18037],"content":"Disallow standard users from changing the PIN or password"},{"content":"This policy setting allows you to configure whether standard users are allowed to change the PIN or password that is used to protect the operating system drive.","pos":[18039,18199]},{"content":"Policy description","pos":[18325,18343]},{"content":"With this policy setting, you can configure whether standard users are allowed to change the PIN or password used to protect the operating system drive.","pos":[18382,18534]},{"content":"Introduced","pos":[18596,18606]},{"content":"Windows Server 2012 and Windows 8","pos":[18645,18678]},{"content":"Drive type","pos":[18739,18749]},{"content":"Operating system drives","pos":[18788,18811]},{"content":"Policy path","pos":[18873,18884]},{"content":"Computer Configuration\\Administrative Templates\\Windows Components\\BitLocker Drive Encryption\\Operating System Drives","pos":[18923,19040]},{"content":"Conflicts","pos":[19101,19110]},{"content":"None","pos":[19149,19153]},{"content":"When enabled","pos":[19215,19227]},{"content":"Standard users are not allowed to change BitLocker PINs or passwords.","pos":[19266,19335]},{"content":"When disabled or not configured","pos":[19396,19427]},{"content":"Standard users are permitted to change BitLocker PINs or passwords.","pos":[19466,19533]},{"content":"Reference","pos":[19572,19581]},{"content":"To change the PIN or password, the user must be able to provide the current PIN or password.","pos":[19585,19677]},{"content":"This policy setting is applied when you turn on BitLocker.","pos":[19678,19736]},{"pos":[19772,19826],"content":"Configure use of passwords for operating system drives"},{"content":"This policy controls how non-TPM based systems utilize the password protector.","pos":[19828,19906]},{"content":"Used in conjunction with the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Password must meet complexity requirements<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> policy, this policy allows administrators to require password length and complexity for using the password protector.","pos":[19907,20100]},{"content":"By default, passwords must be eight characters in length.","pos":[20101,20158]},{"content":"Complexity configuration options determine how important domain connectivity is for the client.","pos":[20159,20254]},{"content":"For the strongest password security, administrators should choose <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Require password complexity<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> because it requires domain connectivity, and it requires that the BitLocker password meets the same password complexity requirements as domain sign-in passwords.","pos":[20255,20514]},{"content":"Policy description","pos":[20640,20658]},{"content":"With this policy setting, you can specify the constraints for passwords that are used to unlock operating system drives that are protected with BitLocker.","pos":[20697,20851]},{"content":"Introduced","pos":[20913,20923]},{"content":"Windows Server 2012 and Windows 8","pos":[20962,20995]},{"content":"Drive type","pos":[21056,21066]},{"content":"Operating system drives","pos":[21105,21128]},{"content":"Policy path","pos":[21190,21201]},{"content":"Computer Configuration\\Administrative Templates\\Windows Components\\BitLocker Drive Encryption\\Operating System Drives","pos":[21240,21357]},{"content":"Conflicts","pos":[21418,21427]},{"content":"Passwords cannot be used if FIPS-compliance is enabled.","pos":[21466,21521]},{"content":"Note","pos":[21554,21558]},{"content":"The <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;strong&gt;</ph>System cryptography: Use FIPS-compliant algorithms for encryption, hashing, and signing<ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/strong&gt;</ph> policy setting, which is located at <ph id=\"ph3\">&lt;strong&gt;</ph>Computer Configuration\\Windows Settings\\Security Settings\\Local Policies\\Security Options<ph id=\"ph4\">&lt;/strong&gt;</ph> specifies whether FIPS-compliance is enabled.","pos":[21573,21870]},{"content":"When enabled","pos":[21954,21966]},{"content":"Users can configure a password that meets the requirements you define.","pos":[22005,22075]},{"content":"To enforce complexity requirements for the password, select <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;strong&gt;</ph>Require complexity<ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/strong&gt;</ph>.","pos":[22076,22172]},{"content":"When disabled or not configured","pos":[22233,22264]},{"content":"The default length constraint of 8 characters will apply to operating system drive passwords and no complexity checks will occur.","pos":[22303,22432]},{"content":"Reference","pos":[22471,22480]},{"content":"If non-TPM protectors are allowed on operating system drives, you can provision a password, enforce complexity requirements on the password, and configure a minimum length for the password.","pos":[22484,22673]},{"content":"For the complexity requirement setting to be effective, the Group Policy setting <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Password must meet complexity requirements<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>, which is located at <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Computer Configuration<ph id=\"ph1\">\\\\</ph>Windows Settings<ph id=\"ph2\">\\\\</ph>Security Settings<ph id=\"ph3\">\\\\</ph>Account Policies<ph id=\"ph4\">\\\\</ph>Password Policy<ph id=\"ph5\">\\\\</ph><ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> must be also enabled.","pos":[22674,22945]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Note:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>  These settings are enforced when turning on BitLocker, not when unlocking a volume.","pos":[22948,23042]},{"content":"BitLocker allows unlocking a drive with any of the protectors that are available on the drive.","pos":[23043,23137]},{"content":"When set to <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Require complexity<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>, a connection to a domain controller is necessary when BitLocker is enabled to validate the complexity the password.","pos":[23140,23291]},{"content":"When set to <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Allow complexity<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>, a connection to a domain controller is attempted to validate that the complexity adheres to the rules set by the policy.","pos":[23292,23446]},{"content":"If no domain controllers are found, the password will be accepted regardless of actual password complexity, and the drive will be encrypted by using that password as a protector.","pos":[23447,23625]},{"content":"When set to <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Do not allow complexity<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>, there is no password complexity validation.","pos":[23626,23710]},{"content":"Passwords must be at least 8 characters.","pos":[23711,23751]},{"content":"To configure a greater minimum length for the password, enter the desired number of characters in the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Minimum password length<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> box.","pos":[23752,23886]},{"pos":[23888,24013],"content":"When this policy setting is enabled, you can set the option <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Configure password complexity for operating system drives<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> to:"},{"content":"Allow password complexity","pos":[24019,24044]},{"content":"Do not allow password complexity","pos":[24049,24081]},{"content":"Require password complexity","pos":[24086,24113]},{"pos":[24155,24239],"content":"Require additional authentication at startup (Windows Server 2008 and Windows Vista)"},{"content":"This policy setting is used to control what unlock options are available for computers running Windows Server 2008 or Windows Vista.","pos":[24241,24373]},{"content":"Policy description","pos":[24499,24517]},{"content":"With this policy setting, you can control whether the BitLocker Setup Wizard on computers running Windows Vista or Windows Server 2008 can set up an additional authentication method that is required each time the computer starts.","pos":[24556,24785]},{"content":"Introduced","pos":[24847,24857]},{"content":"Windows Server 2008 and Windows Vista","pos":[24896,24933]},{"content":"Drive type","pos":[24994,25004]},{"content":"Operating system drives (Windows Server 2008 and Windows Vista)","pos":[25043,25106]},{"content":"Policy path","pos":[25168,25179]},{"content":"Computer Configuration\\Administrative Templates\\Windows Components\\BitLocker Drive Encryption\\Operating System Drives","pos":[25218,25335]},{"content":"Conflicts","pos":[25396,25405]},{"content":"If you choose to require an additional authentication method, other authentication methods cannot be allowed.","pos":[25444,25553]},{"content":"When enabled","pos":[25615,25627]},{"content":"The BitLocker Setup Wizard displays the page that allows the user to configure advanced startup options for BitLocker.","pos":[25666,25784]},{"content":"You can further configure setting options for computers with or without a TPM.","pos":[25785,25863]},{"content":"When disabled or not configured","pos":[25924,25955]},{"content":"The BitLocker Setup Wizard displays basic steps that allow users to enable BitLocker on computers with a TPM.","pos":[25994,26103]},{"content":"In this basic wizard, no additional startup key or startup PIN can be configured.","pos":[26104,26185]},{"content":"Reference","pos":[26223,26232]},{"content":"On a computer with a compatible TPM, two authentication methods can be used at startup to provide added protection for encrypted data.","pos":[26236,26370]},{"content":"When the computer starts, it can require users to insert a USB drive that contains a startup key.","pos":[26371,26468]},{"content":"It can also require users to enter a 4-digit to 20-digit startup PIN.","pos":[26469,26538]},{"content":"A USB drive that contains a startup key is needed on computers without a compatible TPM.","pos":[26540,26628]},{"content":"Without a TPM, BitLocker-encrypted data is protected solely by the key material that is on this USB drive.","pos":[26629,26735]},{"content":"There are two options for TPM-enabled computers or devices:","pos":[26737,26796]},{"content":"Configure TPM startup PIN","pos":[26802,26827]},{"content":"Allow startup PIN with TPM","pos":[26837,26863]},{"content":"Require startup PIN with TPM","pos":[26872,26900]},{"content":"Do not allow startup PIN with TPM","pos":[26909,26942]},{"content":"Configure TPM startup key